<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-424-827  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 424 827.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 11 1990 v4 n30 p97(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Aapps facing financial strain as founder files two suits.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Aapps Corp, of Sunnyvale, CA, is facing extremely criticalfinancial problems that are compounded by a pair of lawsuits bythe company's founder and former president.andP;  Jonathan Whitman,still a major stockholder and a member of the board, charged thecompany with violating its obligations to allow him to examine itsbooks.andP;  He is also suing for breach of contract for failing to payhim fees due under a consulting contract he signed when he gave upthe company presidency earlier this year.andP;  The company is seekingfirmer financial footing through financial and product-developmentalliances with other companies.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Aapps Corp. (cases).andO;Topic:     Financial StabilityLaw Suit.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Henry NorrandM;Sunnyvale, Calif.andP;  -- Aapps Corp., the high-profile developer of videodisplay boards for the Mac, is faced with financial problems the company'sCEO acknowledges are &quot;extremely critical.&quot;andM;Compounding the company's difficulties is a pair of lawsuits by JonathanWhitman, Aapps' founder and former president.andP;  Whitman, CEO of PreferredPublishers Inc. of Memphis, Tenn., and still a major stockholder in Aapps anda member of its board, filed one complaint in April alleging that Aapps hadviolated its obligations under Tennessee law to allow him to examine itsbooks.andM;Aapps is registered in Tennessee.andP;  Whitman said he owns 26 percent of thecompany.andP;  Frank Brooks, the company's CEO, owns 31 percent, while SiliconValley entrepreneur Nolan Bushnell owns 15 percent, according to Whitman.andM;The second suit, filed in July, accuses Aapps of breach of contract forfailing to pay Whitman fees due under a consulting contract he signed when hegave up the Aapps' presidency early this year (see MacWEEK, March 13).andM;Brooks said he was not at liberty to discuss details of the cases whilelitigation is in progress, but he admitted that &quot;things are tight as a tickright now.&quot; The company, he said, hopes to get back on firmer footing byforming financial and product-development alliances with one or more othercompanies.andP;  Negotiations with several possible partners were under way lastweek, and Brooks said an announcement could be forthcoming within days.andM;&quot;I am committed to making this thing work, and I've still got a few legs tokick,&quot; Brooks said.andP;  &quot;It's definitely a tough time, but it looks like thingsare working out.&quot;andM;Whitman, charging that Aapps has stalled legal proceedings and failed tocomply with the terms of a temporary restraining order he obtained thisspring, said his attorneys now are seeking a contempt of court citationagainst Aapps.andM;&quot;I am very concerned about some of the company's financial arrangements,&quot;Whitman said.andP;  &quot;They haven't given me access to the information.&quot; Whitmansaid he was afraid that Aapps may be misleading potential investors and thatas a director he could be held liable.andM;&quot;The straw that broke the camel's back,&quot; Whitman said, &quot;was [Aapps] sent 22people to Macworld Expo in Boston and put them up at the Marriott Long Wharf,just after telling me that [the company] couldn't comply with the terms of mycontract.&quot;andM;Brooks said, &quot;I really, really regret that Jonathan has found it necessary tofile a suit&quot; over what he called a &quot;labor dispute.&quot;andM;For his part, Whitman said he feared that Aapps' management has succumbed to&quot;the crash-and-burn mentality of California companies: You get what you canout, then settle elsewhere.andM;&quot;You can't do that in Memphis,&quot; Whitman said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>